\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Layered architecture of the SurtGIS workspace. Arrows indicate compile-time crate dependencies. The I/O layer provides raster data structures and GeoTIFF / cloud-format readers; the compute layer hosts all algorithms and the parallel-execution adapters; the bindings layer publishes the same algorithm surface to four execution targets (CLI, desktop GUI, browser via WebAssembly, and Python via PyO3). Every binding consumes the same compute layer, so a slope computation in a Python notebook executes the same Rust function as the CLI.}}{5}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:architecture}{{1}{5}{Layered architecture of the SurtGIS workspace. Arrows indicate compile-time crate dependencies. The I/O layer provides raster data structures and GeoTIFF / cloud-format readers; the compute layer hosts all algorithms and the parallel-execution adapters; the bindings layer publishes the same algorithm surface to four execution targets (CLI, desktop GUI, browser via WebAssembly, and Python via PyO3). Every binding consumes the same compute layer, so a slope computation in a Python notebook executes the same Rust function as the CLI}{figure.1}{}}
